WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Guest 1]: I.V.M.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:28.720
[Amit Varma]: Are you a different person when you are in a

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:30.840
[Amit Varma]: crowd than when you are alone?

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:32.720
[Amit Varma]: I know I am.

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes you adjust your behavior to fit the social norms expected in a given situation.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.980
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes you are anxious either to fit in or to impress.

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:45.800
[Amit Varma]: You have a performative self, perhaps even different performative selves for different

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:46.800
[Amit Varma]: situations.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:52.240
[Amit Varma]: But maybe being in a crowd doesn't change you as much as it amplifies some part of your

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:53.440
[Amit Varma]: character.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:58.640
[Amit Varma]: In a cricket stadium, you cheer louder for your favorite team and feel deeper emotion.

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:02.720
[Amit Varma]: And maybe when you are part of an angry crowd, baying for the blood of someone who is not

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:07.960
[Amit Varma]: from these parts or who is not part of your community, your baser instincts get aroused

00:02:07.960 --> 00:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and you do things you would never do if you were alone.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.440
[Amit Varma]: You hit somebody, you hurt somebody, maybe you kill somebody.

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:21.640
[Amit Varma]: Are you a different person when you are in a crowd than when you are alone?

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:27.080
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:28.080
[Unknown]: science.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:29.080
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:38.280
[Amit Varma]: Last week, the Supreme Court asked the Indian Parliament to enact a new law against lynching.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:44.040
[Amit Varma]: I wrote a post in the group blog I edit, Pragati Express at express.thinkpragati.com, arguing

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:47.120
[Amit Varma]: that this was just virtue signaling by the court.

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:50.360
[Amit Varma]: There were already laws against beating people, against killing people.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:54.880
[Amit Varma]: There are even laws that can be used to prosecute people who spread fake news on WhatsApp.

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:59.080
[Amit Varma]: A new law would not cover anything that isn't already covered.

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:04.400
[Amit Varma]: Our problem is not that we don't have enough laws, but that we don't have the rule of law.

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:08.120
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes the state doesn't have the will to prosecute certain crimes.

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:14.160
[Amit Varma]: And even when it does, often when it does, there is not enough state capacity to prosecute

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:15.320
[Amit Varma]: them.

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:18.720
[Amit Varma]: Creating a new law is not going to solve these problems.

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, the topic for today's show is crowd violence in India.

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:26.840
[Amit Varma]: And my guests today are Madhav Chandravarkar and Alok Prasanna Kumar.

